'''Campo Santo''' (Latin, ''[[campus sanctus]]'', "holy field") is an Italian and Spanish name for a burial-place or [[cemetery]]. 

The term derives from the Campo Santo at Pisa, the name given to a novel city initiative begun in the thirteenth century, which led to the formal design and laying-out of Europe's first medieval extra-mural burial ground or cemetery (i.e. a place of general burial separate from a church and its churchyard). The idea was not taken up widely elsewhere in Europe until after the Reformation, when several further extra-mural burial grounds or early cemeteries became established, e.g. at Geneva and in German principalities.

